    "### Strategic Foundation for 2025",
    "2024 established RavenStack as a viable B2B collaboration platform with strong product-market fit in engineering and product teams at mid-market companies. The 2025 strategy will focus on three vectors: AI-powered features to differentiate from competitors, Enterprise deepening to grow our highest-value segment, and operational scaling to handle the volume we expect from our growing customer base."
  ].join("\n"), folder);


  // ── Doc 3: Competitor Analysis: AcmeSaaS ──
  createDocInFolder("Competitor Analysis: AcmeSaaS", [
    "# Competitor Analysis: AcmeSaaS",
    "",
    "Prepared by: Marcus Rivera, Product Strategy",
    "Date: November 2025",
    "Classification: Internal — Do Not Share Externally",
    "Review cycle: Updated quarterly (next update: February 2026)",
    "",
    "## Company Overview",
    "",
    "AcmeSaaS is a direct competitor in the B2B collaboration space, founded in 2020 with headquarters in Austin, TX. They recently raised a $50M Series C led by Benchmark, bringing total funding to $82M. They claim 2,000+ customers across industries with particular strength in HealthTech and EdTech — areas where RavenStack has 96 and 79 accounts respectively.",
    "",
    "AcmeSaaS was founded by former Atlassian executives who saw an opportunity to build a modern, AI-first collaboration platform for regulated industries. Their initial focus was HealthTech compliance workflows, which they later expanded to EdTech, FinTech, and general B2B. This HealthTech heritage gives them an advantage in compliance features that we are still building toward.",
    "",
    "Their executive team includes CEO Maria Santos (ex-Atlassian VP), CTO Dan White (ex-Google Cloud), and VP Product Rachel Kim (ex-Notion). The team has strong enterprise sales DNA, which is reflected in their go-to-market approach.",
    "",
    "## Product Comparison",
    "",
    "### AcmeSaaS Strengths",
    "",
    "#### 1. Superior Mobile Experience",
    "Their mobile app has 4.7 stars on iOS and 4.5 stars on Android, with over 50,000 downloads. Our web-only approach is a significant competitive disadvantage, particularly for field teams in HealthTech and sales teams in FinTech who need mobile access to dashboards and notifications. In competitive deals, we have lost at least 8 opportunities in Q3-Q4 2025 where mobile was cited as a deciding factor.",
    "",
    "#### 2. Built-in Time Tracking with Invoicing",
    "Our Time Tracking feature (2,670 total uses in 2025) covers basic hour logging, but it lacks invoicing integration. AcmeSaaS connects time entries directly to client billing, generating invoices automatically. This is particularly valuable for consulting firms and agencies. Three of our churned accounts in Q4 specifically mentioned this gap.",
    "",
    "#### 3. AI Capabilities at GA",
    "AcmeSaaS launched their AI assistant ('AcmeAI') to general availability in May 2025, six months before our earliest planned GA date (AI Search in January 2026). AcmeAI offers document summarization, task auto-creation, and meeting transcript analysis. While our AI features (AI Search: 492 uses, AI Copilot: 376 uses, Smart Alerts: 378 uses, AI Agent Builder: 367 uses, AI Summary: 356 uses) are all still in beta, their GA status means customers get committed SLAs and enterprise support for AI features.",
    "",
    "Our beta error rates (AI Search: 5.5%, AI Summary: 4.5%, AI Agent Builder: 4.9%, AI Copilot: 7.2%, Smart Alerts: 7.4%) are competitive or better than AcmeAI's reported 6% error rate. However, the beta label creates perception risk. Enterprise procurement teams prefer GA features with committed uptime guarantees.",
    "",
    "#### 4. Security Certifications",
    "AcmeSaaS holds SOC 2 Type II, HIPAA, and ISO 27001 certifications. We currently have none of these, though SOC 2 Type II is in progress (target Q2 2026). This is a hard blocker for many Enterprise deals in FinTech and HealthTech. Our security posture is strong (encryption at rest and in transit, SSO, audit logs, regular pen testing) but the lack of formal certification makes procurement teams nervous.",
    "",
    "### AcmeSaaS Weaknesses",
    "",
    "#### 1. No Real-Time Collaboration",
    "AcmeSaaS relies on async document sharing — their document editor is a rich-text editor without simultaneous multi-user editing. Our Document Editor (3,312 uses) and Real-time Chat (3,202 uses) are genuine differentiators. Teams that need real-time collaboration (design reviews, pair programming, live QBRs) strongly prefer our platform.",
    "",
    "#### 2. Higher Pricing",
    "AcmeSaaS Enterprise: $279/seat/month vs our $199/seat/month — a 40% premium. Their Pro equivalent is $149/seat vs our $79. Their Basic is $49/seat vs our $29. Across all tiers, we are significantly cheaper. For a typical Enterprise deployment of 30 seats, the annual cost difference is ($279 - $199) x 30 x 12 = $28,800/year.",
    "",
    "#### 3. Limited Integrations",
    "AcmeSaaS has 12 native integrations vs our Integrations Hub with 8 technology partners and growing. While their integration count is higher, ours are deeper — our GitHub, Jira, and Salesforce integrations support bidirectional sync, while theirs are read-only. The Integrations Hub (3,457 uses in 2025, our 3rd most-used feature) is a key competitive advantage.",
    "",
    "#### 4. Weak Project Management",
    "AcmeSaaS offers Kanban-only project management. We provide Sprint Planning (3,263 uses), Gantt Charts (2,756 uses), Dependency Graph (2,445 uses), OKR Tracker (3,429 uses), and Kanban Board (2,934 uses). For engineering teams running agile sprints, our project management suite is significantly more capable.",
    "",
    "## Market Position",
    "",
    "AcmeSaaS targets mid-market companies with 50-500 employees, primarily in regulated industries (HealthTech, FinTech, EdTech). Their Series C funding gives them a war chest for sales hiring and marketing, but their higher pricing limits their addressable market in price-sensitive segments.",
    "",
    "RavenStack's strength is in smaller teams scaling up. Our Basic tier ($29/seat) gives us a land-and-expand advantage that AcmeSaaS cannot match with their $49 entry point. Our 168 Basic accounts create a pipeline for Pro (178) and Enterprise (154) upsell. The upgrade path is proven: customers who start on Basic and upgrade to Pro have a 95% retention rate.",
    "",
    "Geographic overlap is significant: both companies are US-heavy (our 291 accounts, ~58% of total). However, AcmeSaaS has stronger EU presence due to their earlier GDPR compliance investment. Our planned EU data residency (Q2 2026) will close this gap.",
    "",
    "## Key Metrics Comparison (estimated)",
    "",
    "- AcmeSaaS ARR: ~$40M (estimated from funding round press release and employee count of ~200)",
    "- RavenStack ARR: $27.3M (based on $2.27M Dec MRR x 12)",
    "- AcmeSaaS churn: ~8% annual (industry reports and Glassdoor employee reviews mentioning churn targets)",
    "- RavenStack churn: 600 events across 500 accounts — needs reduction. Our absolute churn count is high, but many events are from small Basic accounts.",
    "- AcmeSaaS NPS: estimated 40-50 (from G2 reviews)",
    "- RavenStack NPS: not formally measured (recommendation: implement in Q1 2026)",
    "- AcmeSaaS employees: ~200",
    "- RavenStack employees: 87",
    "",
    "## Win/Loss Analysis (Q3-Q4 2025)",
    "",
    "David Kim's sales team tracked 45 competitive deals against AcmeSaaS in Q3-Q4 2025:",
    "- Won 28 (62% win rate)",
    "- Lost 17 (38%)",
    "",
    "Reasons for winning:",
    "- Pricing advantage (cited in 22 of 28 wins)",
    "- Better project management features (cited in 18 of 28 wins)",
    "- Real-time collaboration (cited in 15 of 28 wins)",
    "",
    "Reasons for losing:",
    "- Security certifications (cited in 12 of 17 losses — our biggest competitive gap)",
    "- Mobile app (cited in 8 of 17 losses)",
    "- AI feature GA status (cited in 7 of 17 losses)",
    "",
    "## Recommendations",
    "",
    "### Immediate (Q1 2026)",
    "- Accelerate AI feature graduation — AcmeSaaS's GA AI is winning deals in our pipeline. AI Search GA in January is critical.",
    "- Pursue SOC 2 Type II certification — blocking Enterprise deals in HealthTech and FinTech. Every month of delay costs us an estimated 3-5 Enterprise deals.",
    "- Implement NPS measurement to quantify customer satisfaction vs AcmeSaaS",
    "",
    "### Medium-Term (Q2-Q3 2026)",
    "- Build mobile app — competitive gap widening. AcmeSaaS's mobile downloads are growing ~20% QoQ.",
    "- Add time tracking invoicing integration to neutralize their consulting-firm advantage",
    "- HIPAA certification to compete in HealthTech head-to-head",
    "",
    "### Long-Term (Q4 2026+)",
    "- Leverage pricing advantage in competitive deals — create a formal competitive pricing program with David Kim's team",
    "- Build vertical-specific features for HealthTech and EdTech to attack their stronghold",
    "- Consider strategic partnership or acqui-hire of a compliance-focused startup to accelerate certification timeline"
  ].join("\n"), folder);


  // ── Doc 4: Competitor Analysis: NimbusApp ──
  createDocInFolder("Competitor Analysis: NimbusApp", [
    "# Competitor Analysis: NimbusApp",
    "",
    "Prepared by: Marcus Rivera, Product Strategy",
    "Date: October 2025",
    "Classification: Internal — Do Not Share Externally",
    "Review cycle: Updated quarterly (next update: January 2026)",
    "",
    "## Company Overview",
    "",
    "NimbusApp is a newer entrant in the B2B collaboration space, founded in 2022 by former GitHub engineering leaders. They focus exclusively on DevTools and Cybersecurity verticals, which are our two largest verticals — DevTools (113 accounts, 35 Enterprise) and Cybersecurity (100 accounts, 31 Enterprise). They have raised $15M Series A led by a16z and claim approximately 400 customers.",
    "",
    "NimbusApp's thesis is that general-purpose collaboration tools (including RavenStack, AcmeSaaS, Monday.com, and Asana) are too broad to serve engineering teams well. They have built a vertically integrated platform that connects directly to the developer workflow: GitHub/GitLab repositories, CI/CD pipelines, incident management tools, and code review systems. Their tagline is 'collaboration built for people who ship code.'",
    "",
    "The founding team consists of CEO Lisa Chang (ex-GitHub VP Engineering), CTO Ray Patel (ex-GitLab Principal Engineer), and VP Product Sam Lee (ex-Linear Head of Product). Their engineering pedigree gives them credibility with DevTools buyers that we need to actively counter.",
    "",
    "## Product Comparison",
    "",
    "### NimbusApp Strengths",
    "",
    "#### 1. Deep Git Integration",
    "NimbusApp's sprint planning feature automatically creates tasks from git commits, links pull requests to project milestones, and generates velocity metrics from merge frequency. Our Sprint Planning (3,263 total uses) is well-used but does not have this level of code-awareness. For engineering teams that live in GitHub/GitLab, NimbusApp's integration is genuinely superior.",
    "",
    "Their approach is to treat the git repository as the source of truth and derive project management state from code activity. This means that sprint boards update automatically when PRs are merged, burndown charts reflect actual code output rather than manual status updates, and retrospectives include automated metrics on cycle time, review time, and deployment frequency.",
    "",
    "#### 2. Faster Onboarding",
    "NimbusApp claims a 15-minute average time from signup to first meaningful action, compared to our estimated 45 minutes (based on Li Wei's user research from September 2025). Their onboarding is streamlined because they support fewer use cases — they do not need to ask about vertical, team type, or role. They assume the user is an engineer and present a developer-centric initial experience.",
    "",
    "In our onboarding research, 6 of 12 interviewees mentioned feeling 'overwhelmed' by the initial RavenStack dashboard. This is a direct consequence of our 40-feature breadth — an advantage in product depth but a liability in first-time user experience.",
    "",
    "#### 3. Built-in CI/CD Pipeline Visualization",
    "NimbusApp includes a visual CI/CD pipeline builder and monitoring dashboard. Users can see their deployment pipelines, track build status, and trigger deployments from within the collaboration platform. We have no equivalent feature. Our API Webhooks (2,802 uses) can connect to CI/CD tools, but it requires manual configuration.",
    "",
    "#### 4. Developer-First Design",
    "NimbusApp's UI is designed by and for developers. It includes dark mode by default, keyboard shortcuts for every action, a command palette (similar to VS Code's Cmd+P), and markdown-first editing. Our design system (Nimbus UI v3.2, maintained by Li Wei) is polished and accessible but targets a broader audience including PMs, designers, and executives. DevTools buyers sometimes perceive our UI as 'too corporate' or 'not built for engineers.'",
    "",
    "### NimbusApp Weaknesses",
    "",
    "#### 1. No Multi-Vertical Support",
    "NimbusApp cannot expand beyond DevTools and Cybersecurity without significant product changes. Their entire feature set assumes a technical user persona. They have no equivalent to our Budget Tracker (2,534 uses), Stakeholder Map (3,189 uses), Portfolio View (2,400 uses), or Client Portal (2,356 uses). Companies that have both engineering and business teams cannot use NimbusApp as a single platform — they would need a separate tool for non-engineering workflows.",
    "",
    "This is a structural advantage for RavenStack. Our 40 features serve cross-functional teams, which means we get deployed org-wide rather than just in engineering. An org-wide deployment of 50 seats at $199/seat generates $9,950/month, while NimbusApp's typical deployment of 15 engineering seats at $99/seat generates $1,485/month. Our average deal size is 6.7x larger.",
    "",
    "#### 2. No AI Capabilities",
    "NimbusApp has no AI features at all. No document summarization, no semantic search, no automated task creation, nothing. Our AI Search (492 beta uses), AI Copilot (376 uses), AI Agent Builder (367 uses), AI Summary (356 uses), and Smart Alerts (378 uses) collectively represent a significant capability gap. As AI becomes table-stakes in B2B SaaS, NimbusApp will face increasing pressure to build or buy AI capabilities.",
    "",
    "#### 3. Single Pricing Tier ($99/seat/month)",
    "NimbusApp has one tier at $99/seat/month. No Basic tier for small teams, no Enterprise tier with premium features. This means they cannot execute a land-and-expand motion. Our Basic ($29) → Pro ($79) → Enterprise ($199) upgrade path is proven: customers who upgrade from Basic to Pro have 95% retention. NimbusApp can only grow revenue by adding seats to existing accounts, not by upgrading them to higher tiers.",
    "",
    "#### 4. Limited Analytics and Reporting",
    "NimbusApp has basic project dashboards but no equivalent to our Dashboard Builder (3,446 uses, 4th most-used), Custom Reports (3,098 uses), OKR Tracker (3,429 uses, 5th most-used), or Data Export (3,306 uses). Engineering managers who need to report upward to VPs and the C-suite find NimbusApp's analytics insufficient for executive-level communication.",
    "",
    "## Risk Assessment",
    "",
    "### High Risk: DevTools Account Poaching",
    "NimbusApp could poach our DevTools accounts (113 total, 35 Enterprise). Their engineering-specific UX is more targeted, and their git integration is genuinely better. We estimate that 20-30% of our DevTools accounts are 'at risk' of switching if NimbusApp aggressively markets to them.",
    "",
    "The financial impact would be significant: 35 Enterprise DevTools accounts at an average of $10,732/month MRR = $375,620/month at risk. Even losing 10% (3-4 accounts) would represent $35K-$40K in lost monthly MRR.",
    "",
    "### Medium Risk: Cybersecurity Vertical Competition",
    "Our Cybersecurity vertical (100 accounts, 31 Enterprise) is also exposed, though less so than DevTools. Cybersecurity teams value our Audit Logs and Approval Workflows features, which NimbusApp lacks. However, security teams often include developers who prefer NimbusApp's workflow.",
    "",
    "### Low Risk: Expansion to Other Verticals",
    "NimbusApp expanding beyond DevTools/Cybersecurity to FinTech, HealthTech, or EdTech is unlikely in the near term. Their product architecture assumes engineering workflows. Rebuilding for business users would require a fundamental pivot. However, if they raise a large Series B, they could acqui-hire a general-purpose collaboration team.",
    "",
    "### Emerging Risk: AI Features",
    "NimbusApp has no AI features today, but their a16z backing and engineering talent pool make it likely they will add AI capabilities in 2026. If they build AI features specifically for developers (code review assistants, automated documentation, AI-powered sprint planning), they could leapfrog our general-purpose AI features in the DevTools vertical. Monitor their product announcements closely.",
    "",
    "## Competitive Strategy Recommendations",
    "",
    "### Defensive: Protect DevTools and Cybersecurity",
    "- Build deeper git integration for Sprint Planning and OKR Tracker. Invest 2 sprints in Q1 2026 to add GitHub PR linking, automated sprint updates from merge events, and velocity metrics from git activity.",
    "- Create DevTools-specific onboarding flow that matches NimbusApp's 15-minute time-to-value. Li Wei should prototype a developer persona onboarding path that skips business features and goes straight to Sprint Planning + Kanban Board + Real-time Chat.",
    "- Promote Integrations Hub and API Webhooks to engineering teams through targeted content marketing (DevTools webinars, engineering blog posts, GitHub integration showcase).",
    "",
    "### Offensive: Leverage Our Advantages",
    "- Emphasize cross-functional deployment in competitive deals. NimbusApp can only serve engineering teams; we serve the entire organization. Position RavenStack as the platform that eliminates tool sprawl.",
    "- Highlight our AI features. Even in beta, AI Search (5.5% error rate) and AI Agent Builder (4.9% error rate) are capabilities NimbusApp cannot match.",
    "- Use pricing as a weapon. Our Basic tier at $29 undercuts NimbusApp's $99 by 71%. For price-sensitive DevTools startups, this is a compelling entry point.",
    "",
    "### Intelligence Gathering",
    "- Monitor NimbusApp's job postings for signals about AI hiring, new vertical expansion, or enterprise sales team growth.",
    "- Track their product changelog and release notes monthly. Assign one product analyst to maintain a competitive tracking document.",
    "- Interview churned accounts that went to NimbusApp to understand the exact feature gaps that drove the switch."
  ].join("\n"), folder);


  // ── Doc 5: Product-Eng Sync Notes (Nov 15, 2025) ──
  createDocInFolder("Product-Eng Sync Notes (Nov 15, 2025)", [
    "# Product-Eng Sync Notes — November 15, 2025",
    "",
    "Attendees: Sarah Chen (VP Product), Jake Morrison (Eng Lead), Priya Patel (Data Lead), Li Wei (Design Lead)",
    "Location: Conference Room B (Raven's Nest), San Francisco HQ",
    "Duration: 90 minutes (extended from usual 60 due to Q4 churn review)",
    "Note-taker: Sarah Chen",
    "",
    "## Pre-Meeting Context",
    "",
    "This sync was called with an extended agenda following the preliminary Q4 churn numbers that Priya shared in the #leadership Slack channel on November 13. The numbers showed Q4 churn already at 180 events with 6 weeks remaining in the quarter, putting us on pace for 250+ events — nearly double Q3's 130 events. Sarah requested that all four leads attend (Li Wei normally joins every other session) to align on a coordinated response.",
    "",
    "Supporting documents referenced in this meeting:",
    "- Churn Analysis Q3-Q4 2025 (Priya's spreadsheet, shared November 12)",
    "- Customer Health Score Framework (Priya's draft, shared November 14)",
    "- Beta Feature Telemetry Dashboard (Jake's live dashboard, updated daily)",
    "- User Research: Power User Interviews (Li Wei's report, completed November 10)",
    "",
    "## Agenda Items",
    "",
    "### 1. Q4 Churn Spike Review (35 minutes)",
    "",
    "Sarah opened with the headline number: Q4 churn is projected to reach 251 events by December 31, up from 130 in Q3. She displayed the quarterly breakdown on the conference room screen:",
    "",
    "- 2025-Q1: 52 events (Pricing: 11, Support: 7, Budget: 7, Features: 13, Competitor: 6, Unknown: 8). Refunds: $603.27.",
    "- 2025-Q2: 92 events (Pricing: 15, Support: 15, Budget: 16, Features: 16, Competitor: 20, Unknown: 10). Refunds: $990.30.",
    "- 2025-Q3: 130 events (Pricing: 22, Support: 22, Budget: 23, Features: 21, Competitor: 20, Unknown: 22). Refunds: $2,502.58.",
    "- 2025-Q4 (projected): 251 events (Pricing: 33, Support: 41, Budget: 47, Features: 53, Competitor: 33, Unknown: 44). Refunds: $3,710.32.",
    "",
    "Sarah emphasized that Q4's top reason is features (53 events), which overtook competitor as the leading single reason. She asked Jake for his interpretation.",
    "",
    "Jake noted that the 'features' churn reason aligns with customer complaints about AI Copilot error rate (7.2%). He had reviewed the support tickets associated with churned Enterprise accounts and found that two FinTech Enterprise accounts specifically cited AI Copilot reliability as the reason for leaving. One account had 37 seats ($199 x 37 = $7,363/month MRR) and the other had 22 seats ($199 x 22 = $4,378/month MRR). Together, losing these two accounts represented $11,741 in monthly MRR — equivalent to losing nearly 14 Basic accounts.",
    "",
    "Jake continued: 'The issue is that we marketed AI Copilot as a beta feature, but Enterprise customers treated it as production-ready because it was enabled in their workspace. When it failed 7.2% of the time, they blamed the platform, not the beta label. We need to either improve the error rate or change how we surface beta features to Enterprise accounts.'",
    "",
    "Priya added context from her health score analysis: accounts that used AI Copilot and experienced errors in their first week had a 2.5x higher likelihood of opening support tickets, and accounts with 3+ urgent tickets in a quarter have 4x higher churn rate. 'There is a direct pipeline from AI errors to support tickets to churn,' she said.",
    "",
    "Li Wei shared relevant findings from the power user interviews: 'Power users actually love AI Copilot. 7 of 8 interviewees are using it despite the errors. The difference is that power users understand the beta label and work around errors. Regular users don't have that tolerance.'",
    "",
    "Sarah summarized the discussion: 'So we have two types of feature churn — power users who want AI features to be better, and regular users who are frustrated by AI errors. The fix is different for each group.'",
    "",
    "Action item: Jake to prioritize AI Copilot error rate reduction — target <3% by end of Q1 2026. He noted that the new error handling he deployed to staging has already reduced the rate from 7.2% to 5.8%. The remaining improvement will require model fine-tuning and better input validation.",
    "",
    "Action item: Li Wei to design a 'beta feature guardrails' system that sets clearer expectations for non-power users, including warning dialogs before AI actions and a 'beta quality' badge on all AI-generated output.",
    "",
    "### 2. Support Ticket Trends (20 minutes)",
    "",
    "Priya shared the support ticket dashboard on screen. December support tickets are tracking to 98 (highest month of the year), with 28 urgent tickets (also the highest). For comparison:",
    "",
    "- January 2025: 85 tickets (20 urgent), CSAT 3.94, Resolution 36.5 hours",
    "- July 2025: 70 tickets (20 urgent), CSAT 4.00, Resolution 40.8 hours (worst resolution time)",
    "- September 2025: 96 tickets (23 urgent), CSAT 4.36 (best CSAT of the year), Resolution 34.3 hours",
    "- November 2025: 84 tickets (27 urgent), CSAT 3.82 (below average), Resolution 35.9 hours",
    "- December 2025 (projected): 98 tickets (28 urgent), CSAT 3.84, Resolution 33.8 hours",
    "",
    "Priya highlighted two concerning trends. First, the urgent ticket count is rising independently of total ticket volume — November had 27 urgent tickets out of 84 total (32%), compared to January's 20 out of 85 (24%). Second, CSAT in November was 3.82, which is below the year-to-date average of 3.98 and the worst since April (3.81).",
    "",
    "The team discussed whether the support team needs additional headcount. Emily Rodriguez's team currently has 8 support engineers handling approximately 83 tickets per month on average. Priya calculated that each engineer handles about 10.5 tickets per month, with an average resolution time of 35.6 hours.",
    "",
    "Jake pointed out that many urgent tickets are related to AI feature issues, which require engineering escalation. 'Our support team can't debug AI model failures. We need either AI-specialized support engineers or a dedicated triage path from support to the AI engineering squad.'",
    "",
    "Sarah agreed and noted that the Churn Reduction Initiative Proposal (which she is drafting) will include a request for 3 additional support hires and a new AI-specific support tier.",
    "",
    "Action item: Priya to build a correlation analysis between support tickets and churn events by account. She estimated this would take 2 weeks and would feed into the Customer Health Score Framework validation.",
    "",
    "Action item: Sarah to include support headcount request in the Churn Reduction Initiative Proposal draft (target completion: December 15).",
    "",
    "### 3. AI Feature Beta Status (25 minutes)",
    "",
    "Jake presented the current beta feature performance from the telemetry dashboard:",
    "",
    "- AI Search: 492 total uses, 43 hours total duration, 27 errors, 5.5% error rate, 46 usage records. Status: READY for GA. Feature freeze complete. Documentation in final review. Jake confirmed that the GA launch date is January 15, 2026. The only remaining work is load testing (targeting 10,000 queries/hour) and documentation sign-off.",
    "- Smart Alerts: 378 total uses, 37 hours total duration, 28 errors, 7.4% error rate, 36 usage records. Status: NEEDS WORK. The NLP model for alert condition parsing has low accuracy on complex conditions. Root cause: the model struggles with nested Boolean logic ('alert me when MRR drops AND churn increases BUT NOT if it is Q4'). Jake estimates 4-6 sprints to fix.",
    "- AI Copilot: 376 total uses, 32 hours total duration, 27 errors, 7.2% error rate, 36 usage records. Status: NEEDS WORK. Li Wei's usability study found that 40% of errors come from users attempting unsupported operations (e.g., 'create a presentation' when we only support documents). Better guardrails could cut errors by 40%, bringing the rate to ~4.3%. Combined with model improvements (staging shows 5.8%), Jake believes <3% is achievable by Q2 2026.",
    "- AI Agent Builder: 367 total uses, 35 hours total duration, 18 errors, 4.9% error rate, 37 usage records. Status: CLOSE TO READY. Error rate is already below 5%. The blocker is that Agent Builder requires complex permission management (agents can modify data on behalf of users), and the Enterprise security team (Omar Hassan) needs to complete a security review. Target GA: March 2026.",
    "- AI Summary: 356 total uses, 31 hours total duration, 16 errors, 4.5% error rate, 35 usage records. Status: CLOSE TO READY. Lowest error rate of any AI feature. Minor UX improvements needed (Li Wei identified that the summary format is inconsistent between document types). Target GA: February 2026.",
    "",
    "Jake proposed a phased GA rollout: AI Search (January) → AI Summary (February) → AI Agent Builder (March) → AI Copilot and Smart Alerts (Q2 2026). Sarah approved the timeline.",
    "",
    "Li Wei noted that each AI feature GA launch should include an in-app announcement, updated help documentation, and a blog post. She volunteered to coordinate with Jen Nakamura (Marketing Lead) on the AI Search launch campaign.",
    "",
    "Action item: Jake to create GA readiness plan for AI Search — target launch Jan 15, 2026. Plan should include load testing results, documentation checklist, rollback procedure, and monitoring dashboard.",
    "Action item: Li Wei to run usability study on AI Copilot to identify UX-driven error causes. (Note: Li Wei mentioned she has already conducted 8 interviews for this study. The full report will be shared by November 22.)",
    "Action item: Jake to schedule security review with Omar Hassan for AI Agent Builder — target completion December 15.",
    "",
    "### 4. Video Conferencing Errors (10 minutes)",
    "",
    "Video Conferencing has the highest error count of any feature at 205 errors in 2025 despite 3,294 uses (6.2% error rate). Jake confirmed that the memory leak in the WebRTC layer has been identified and patched. The fix was deployed on November 1, and the error rate has dropped from 6.2% to 2.1% in the 2 weeks since deployment.",
    "",
    "The memory leak caused sessions to crash after approximately 45 minutes of continuous use. The root cause was a circular reference in the media stream cleanup handler that prevented garbage collection. Jake's team found it through heap profiling in a dedicated debugging sprint (Sprint 23).",
    "",
    "Priya asked whether the Video Conferencing errors contributed to churn. Jake estimated that the errors affected approximately 20 accounts heavily (those with daily video meetings) but could not directly attribute churn events to it. Sarah asked Priya to include Video Conferencing error exposure as a factor in the health score model.",
    "",
    "Action item: Jake to monitor Video Conferencing error rate for 4 more weeks to confirm the fix is stable. If the 2.1% rate holds, close the investigation and reallocate the debugging engineer to AI Copilot improvement.",
    "",
    "## Open Discussion (5 minutes)",
    "",
    "Li Wei raised a concern about the upcoming holiday season: 'Several Enterprise accounts have indicated they will pause usage over the holidays. Should we proactively reach out to ensure they reactivate in January?' Sarah agreed and asked Emily Rodriguez (CS Lead, not in attendance) to coordinate a holiday re-engagement campaign for Enterprise accounts.",
    "",
    "Jake mentioned that the engineering team's Q4 OKR progress is at 60% with 6 weeks remaining. The at-risk OKR is 'Reduce P0 incidents from 3/month to 1/month' — they are currently at 2/month, which may not reach the 1/month target. Sarah acknowledged this and noted it would be discussed in the Q4 Engineering OKR review.",
    "",
    "## Action Items Summary",
    "",
    "- Jake: AI Copilot error rate reduction plan (target <3% by Q1 2026 end)",
    "- Jake: AI Search GA readiness plan (launch Jan 15, 2026)",
    "- Jake: Schedule AI Agent Builder security review with Omar Hassan (by Dec 15)",
    "- Jake: Monitor Video Conferencing error rate for 4 weeks",
    "- Li Wei: Beta feature guardrails UX design",
    "- Li Wei: AI Copilot usability study report (by Nov 22)",
    "- Li Wei: Coordinate AI Search launch campaign with Jen Nakamura",
